{"detail":{"ID":1184,"post_author":"1","post_date":"2017-04-06 15:20:09","post_date_gmt":"2017-04-06 15:20:09","post_content":"At the corner of the City Park of Dessau, the building for the <em>Bauhaus Museum<\/em> literally binds together its collection, the temporary exhibits and the city itself. Aspiring to resist the rigor mortis that descends upon things canonized into museums all over the world, the building is organized as a continuous loop feeding off future temporary exhibitions and the city itself to inject continued relevance and vitality into the enduring legacy of the Bauhaus. Back at the Temporary Exhibit Gallery overlooking the Foyer below, visitors can either descend to the entry level or recommence the exhibition cycle again for a closer look at items that might have captured their interest. Made flexible by shortcut connections that allow the visitors to design their own trajectories, this exhibition loop provides conceptual clarity to the structure of the galleries and invites the possibility of repetition, potentially encouraging a more profound knowledge of The Bauhaus Collection. It is said that the future changes the past: the strong continuity between Temporary Exhibits and Permanent Collection generated by the closed loop trajectory encourages, with each new temporary exhibit, the potential of generating fresh views on the history of the Bauhaus, contributing to the vitality of its cultural legacy.","post_title":"<p>Bauhaus Museum Dessau, DE 2015<\/p>","post_excerpt":"","post_status":"publish","comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"closed","post_password":"","post_name":"bauhaus-museum-dessau-de-2015","to_ping":"","pinged":"","post_modified":"2017-05-10 16:40:41","post_modified_gmt":"2017-05-10 16:40:41","post_content_filtered":"","post_parent":0,"guid":"http:\/\/obra.neptuno.digital\/?post_type=projects&#038;p=1184","menu_order":0,"post_type":"projects","post_mime_type":"","comment_count":"0","filter":"raw","ancestors":[],"page_template":